data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_01fb9650c820ccda0069963ff0af9c81908d8d0dc74a25772e","logprobs":[],"output_index":2,"sequence_number":250,"text":"According to Wikipedia, Euler's identity (also known as Euler's equation) is the mathematical equality:\n\n\\[ e^{i\\pi} + 1 = 0 \\]\n\nHere, \\( e \\) is Euler's number (the base of natural logarithms), \\( i \\) is the imaginary unit (satisfying \\( i^2 = -1 \\)), and \\( \\pi \\) is pi, the ratio of a circle's circumference to its diameter.\n\nEuler's identity is celebrated for its mathematical beauty because it connects five fundamental constants — 0, 1, \\( \\pi \\), \\( e \\), and \\( i \\) — using three basic arithmetic operations (addition, multiplication, exponentiation), all in one simple formula. It's a special case of Euler's formula, evaluated at \\( x = \\pi \\):\n\n\\[ e^{ix} = \\cos x + i \\sin x \\implies e^{i\\pi} = -1 \\]\n\nWikipedia notes mathematicians and educators often praise its aesthetic elegance, with quotes likening it to masterpieces in art or poetry. Euler's identity has even been voted as the \"most beautiful theorem in mathematics\" in several polls【4:0†source】."}

